syntheses:
{
  "missing": [
    {
      "gap": "No cross-pillar GPU/fleet budget contention view. Ball (label re-score), body-world (GATE-1b root-cause), court (calv1unet2 retrain) are all separately described as competing for 'the same fleet slot,' but no map treats fleet-hours as a single shared constrained resource with an explicit allocation decision across pillars. Right now three high-severity blockers are each proposing to consume GPU budget independently.",
      "why_it_matters": "Without one owner-visible view of total fleet spend vs. the 3 competing high-value asks, the manager risks either starving the highest-leverage item (GATE-1b, which blocks ALL downstream body/mesh work) or over-committing to a lower-yield retrain (court_unet_v2, which has already regressed once)."
    },
    {
      "gap": "No pillar audits owner-time/bandwidth as a shared constrained resource. Paddle needs an owner 4-marker GT session; data-engine needs 42-84 owner-labeling-hours; product-infra references 'phone tests' and 'game recording' as owner asks; court needs a Roboflow API key re-issue. These are tracked separately per-pillar with no consolidated view of total owner-ask backlog or sequencing priority.",
      "why_it_matters": "Every pillar quietly assumes it can get owner time whenever needed; if the owner's actual bandwidth is the true bottleneck (more than GPU or engineering), several 'needs_revisit' items across pillars are really one shared queue competing for the same person's hours, and no one has ranked that queue."
    },
    {
      "gap": "No security/secrets/PII pillar despite product-infra now handling real user auth (JWT), payment scaffolding (Stripe), and uploaded player video (S3 presigned). No audit map covers secret-rotation discipline, PII/video-retention policy, or auth-token security posture for the new INFRA-0..5 build.",
      "why_it_matters": "This is a real production system now (accounts, uploads, deletes, payments-scaffold) shipping toward real users; a first security review before any account-enabled flag flips live is normal practice and currently absent from every pillar map."
    },
    {
      "gap": "No pillar covers input/capture-quality guardrails for real (non-owner, non-curated) end-user video — e.g., wrong orientation, non-pickleball content, court not visible, poor lighting. Speed-pipeline names P5-5b (ffprobe/orientation pre-flight) as unbuilt with orientation hardcoded to 'landscape' in 2 places, but no map treats 'garbage-in protection for arbitrary end-user uploads' as a first-class product-readiness gap.",
      "why_it_matters": "Every pillar's accuracy work assumes reasonably well-shot pickleball video; without an input-quality gate, real end users will burn GPU dollars and get silently poor/garbage 3D worlds with no diagnosis, undermining the 'trust > novelty' product philosophy the deep-review already established."
    },
    {
      "gap": "No pillar assesses licensing/compliance risk for the training data supply chain — Roboflow's 61,260 dedup pretrain samples (data-engine) and PnLCalib GPL checkpoints (court) are both referenced as load-bearing inputs, but no map checks license terms against the commercial product goal (P7 monetization/Stripe scaffold now exists).",
      "why_it_matters": "If any pretrain corpus or checkpoint carries a non-commercial or copyleft license, that surfaces as a legal blocker only after the product is monetizing — cheap to check now, expensive to discover later."
    }
  ],
  "severity_corrections": [
    {
      "pillar": "speed-pipeline",
      "item": "P5-1's own gate (Wolverine <=400s, Outdoor <=2x, six-run variance, bit-identical foot-slide) has no report.json scoring it against those exact thresholds; the only live attempt at the biggest lever (S4 chunked handoff) regressed and was reverted.",
      "should_be": "high (currently medium)",
      "why": "This is the literal load-bearing evidence behind the project's headline claim ('2141s->532-565s, 3.8x') that's repeated verbatim in the NORTH_STAR PHASE 5 header as settled fact. With the one attempted lever toward the stated floor having regressed and reverted, and no certified pass against the actual gate thresholds, the claimed speed win is currently unverified by its own criteria, not just 'undocumented' — that's a correctness-of-claim issue, not a paperwork gap."
    },
    {
      "pillar": "court",
      "item": "P4-0 (court-profile library) is 0% built and deprioritized behind the still-failing P4-2/P4-3 auto-find epic.",
      "should_be": "high (currently medium)",
      "why": "The map's own text calls P4-0 the 'actual v1 path' that works for the owner's own courts TODAY at low engineering risk, explicitly contrasted against an epic that has now missed its bar across at least 2 wave attempts (best fused 244.3px/212.6px vs a 200px bar) and just committed to a second GPU retrain with no proof of fix. Continuing to starve a near-certain, cheap, real win in favor of doubling down on a repeatedly-missing epic is a bigger opportunity-cost risk to the 'fastest video->3D world' goal than a 'medium' severity implies."
    },
    {
      "pillar": "ball-chain",
      "item": "seed_official's 486-row fine-tune underperformed control on LoSO-mean (0.6404 vs 0.6858), booked as 'small-N noise suspect' but never re-run/resolved.",
      "should_be": "medium (currently low)",
      "why": "seed_official is now the pillar's own declared LoSO winner on real owner-labeled outdoor data (beating both control and stage1_official per the same map's working_well section) and is the presumptive base for further fine-tuning. An unresolved regression signal in the leading candidate's own earlier fine-tune round is a live risk to the very recipe the pillar is about to scale up, not a minor footnote — it should be resolved before more owner-labeling hours are poured into extending that same recipe."
    }
  ],
  "top5_leverage": [
    {
      "item": "GATE-1b world round-trip decode fidelity FAIL (262.35mm vs <=1mm bar; 53.50mm p95 vs <=5mm bar), root cause still untraced",
      "pillar": "body-world",
      "why": "This single defect blocks every downstream body-smoothness and latent-interpolation deliverable across two pillars simultaneously (body-world's own P2-2/latent work AND product-infra-viewer's mesh-cap/playback-quality ceiling) and is explicitly named the wave-7 #1 priority after ball retrain. It sits on the critical path to 'most accurate 3D world' and nothing downstream can be trusted until it's root-caused, yet no one has traced it past ruling out checkpoint-key mismatch."
    },
    {
      "item": "Ball held-out labeled-corpus volume gap (1121 of the required >=10-20k rows, ~5.6-11.2% there) blocking the pre-registered M1/M3 held-out shot",
      "pillar": "ball-chain / data-engine",
      "why": "This is the literal definition-of-done gate for BALL, and BALL detection quality is upstream of arc-solving, BVP, Magnus, and event fusion — every other ball-chain win to date (LoSO ranking, preprocessing fix, span-protection) is internal-val only and non-promotable until this volume bar clears. It is also the single biggest identified bottleneck across all 10 pillars by the maps' own language ('the single biggest bottleneck on the critical path')."
    },
    {
      "item": "Paddle fused 6-DOF estimator built, measured, and accepted, but still not wired into the default E2E pipeline (P3-1) — 'oldest BUILT-NOT-WIRED orphan, 4 waves'",
      "pillar": "paddle-racket",
      "why": "This is the cheapest, highest-certainty win of the five: the hard engineering (fusion, ablation, acceptance) is already done and measured; wiring it is comparatively low-risk/low-cost integration work that has simply been re-sequenced away four waves running. It's the one item on this list that doesn't need new research, an owner session, or GPU spend — only dispatch."
    },
    {
      "item": "Browser-verify (live-viewer regression check) blocked by the INFRA-3 sign-in gate for 2 consecutive waves, with every recent GPU-decisive run closing 'numeric-only'",
      "pillar": "product-infra-viewer",
      "why": "This is the manager's own historically-proven bug-catching mechanism (it caught the fail-open HUD bug in 2026-07-05) sitting disabled exactly while multiple pillars (body-world mesh-cap, ball, court) are landing viewer-facing changes. Losing it for 2+ waves in a row is a silent, compounding risk to every 'looks done' claim being made elsewhere, and the fix (a dev-bypass) is small and has simply not been picked up."
    },
    {
      "item": "P4-0 court-profile library (0% built) deprioritized behind the still-failing P4-2/P4-3 auto-find epic, despite being named the actual v1 path that already works for the owner's own courts",
      "pillar": "court",
      "why": "This is real, near-certain product value (the owner's own courts, today) being left completely unbuilt while GPU budget and engineering attention keep chasing an auto-find epic that has missed its ≤200px bar on every attempt so far (244.3px/212.6px best) and just committed a second retrain with no proof of fix yet. Redirecting even partial effort here is a low-risk, high-certainty way to move the 'fastest video->3D world' goal forward for the owner's actual use case while the harder epic keeps iterating."
    }
  ]
}
